Figure 5: The decomposition results using our Decom-Net and LIME on Bookshelf in LOL dataset. In our results, the reÔ¨Çectance of the low-light image resembles the reÔ¨Çectance of the normal-light image except for the ampliÔ¨Åed noise in dark regions occurred in real scenes.

Raw images contain more information than the converted results. When operating on raw images, all calculations used to generate pixel values are performed in one step on the base data, making the result more accurate. 1000 raw images in RAISE [4] are used to synthesize low-light images. Interface provided by Adobe Lightroom is used and we try different kinds of parameters to make the histogram of Y channel Ô¨Åt the result in low-light images. Final parameter conÔ¨Åguration can be found in the supplementary material. As shown in Fig. 4, the illumination distribution of synthetic images matches that of low-light images. Finally we resize these raw images to 400 √ó 600 and convert them to Portable Network Graphics format.

4 Experiments
4.1 Implementation Details
Our LOL dataset mentioned in Sec. 3 with 500 image pairs is divided into 485 pairs for training and another 15 ones for evaluation. So the net-work is trained on 485 real-case image pairs as well as 1000 synthetic ones. The whole network is light-weighted since we empirically Ô¨Ånd it already enough for our purpose. The Decom-Net takes 5 convolutional layers with a ReLU activation between 2 conv-layers without ReLU. The Enhance-Net consists of 3 down-sampling blocks and 3 up-sampling ones. We Ô¨Årst train the Decom-Net and the Enhance-Net, then Ô¨Åne-tune the network end-to-end using stochastic gradient descent

