(a) LIME

(b) JED

(c) Retinex-Net

Figure 7: The joint denoising results using different methods on Wardrobe in LOL Dataset.

with multiple exposure levels. DICM collected 69 images with commercial digital cameras. We compare our Retinex-Net with four state-of-the-art methods, including de-hazing based method (DeHz) [5], naturalness preserved enhancement algorithm (NPE) [23], simultaneous reÔ¨Çectance and illumination estimation algorithm (SRIE) [8], and illumination map estimation based (LIME) [9].
Fig. 6 shows visual comparison on three natural images. More results can be found in the supplementary Ô¨Åle. As shown in every red rectangle, our method brightens up the objects buried in dark lightness enough without overexposure, which beneÔ¨Åts from the learningbased image decomposition method and the multi-scale tailored illumination map. Compared with LIME, our results are not partially over-exposed (see the leaves in Still lives and the outside leaves in Room). The objects have no dark edges, compared with DeHz, which beneÔ¨Åts from the weighted TV loss term (see edges on the houses in Street).
4.4 Joint Low-Light Enhancement and Denoising
Considering the comprehensive performance, BM3D [3] is used as the denoising operation in Retinex-Net. As noise is unevenly ampliÔ¨Åed on reÔ¨Çectance, we use a illumination relative strategy (see supplementary material). We compare our joint-denoising Retinex-Net with two methods, one is LIME with denoising post-processing, the other is JED [22], a recent joint low-light enhancement and denoising method. As shown in Fig. 7, details are better preserved by Retinex-Net while LIME and JED blur the edges.

5 Conclusion
In this paper, a deep Retinex decomposition method is proposed, which can learn to decompose the observed image into reÔ¨Çectance and illumination in a data-driven way without the ground truth of decomposed reÔ¨Çectance and illumination. Subsequent light enhancement on illumination and denoising operations on reÔ¨Çectance are introduced. The decomposition network and low-light enhancement network are trained end-to-end. Experimental results show that our method produces visually pleasing enhancement results as well as a good representation of image decomposition.

